06449nam a22009375i 9780812205909DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20112009pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979724106  a97808122059097 a10.9783/97808122059092doi  a(DE-B1597)449424  a(OCoLC)794702135  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPOL0320002bisacsh04a355.400aGetting Out :bHistorical Perspectives on Leaving Iraq /ced. by Nicolaus Mills, Michael Walzer. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (168 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tLESSONS FROM THE PAST -- t1. No Exit but Victory: Britain and the American Colonies -- t2. America and the Philippines: The Graceful Withdrawal -- t3. India and Britain: The Consequences of Leaving Too Soon -- t4. The Surprising Success: The United States and Korea -- t5. France and Algeria: Claim Victory and Au Revoir -- t6. Vietnam and the United States: The Price of Intransigence -- t7. The Gates of Gaza and the Limits of Power: Israel and Gaza -- tGETTING IN / GETTING OUT -- t8. 9/11 and the Road to Iraq -- t9 The Persistence of Empire -- t10. Departing Responsibly -- t11. It Isn’t Over -- tContributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEventually every conqueror, every imperial power, every occupying army gets out. Why do they decide to leave? And how do political and military leaders manage withdrawal? Do they take with them those who might be at risk if left behind? What are the immediate consequences of departure? For Michael Walzer and Nicolaus Mills, now is the time to ask those questions about exiting—and to worry specifically about the difficulties certain to arise as we leave—Iraq.Getting Out approaches these issues in two sections. The first, entitled "Lessons Learned," examines seven historical cases of how and how not to withdraw: Britain's departure from the American colonies and from India, the French withdrawal from Algeria, Israel's unilateral withdrawal from Gaza, and the U.S. decision to leave (or not leave) the Philippines, Korea, and Vietnam. These cases offer a comparative perspective and an opportunity to learn from the history of political and military retreats.The second section, "Exiting Iraq," begins with an introduction to just how the United States got into Iraq and continues with an examination of how the U.S. might leave from a diversity of voices, ranging from those who believe that the Iraq war has produced no real good to those who hope for a decent ending. In addition to essays by volume editors Walzer and Mills, Getting Out features contributions by Shlomo Avineri, Rajeev Bhargava, David Bromwich, Frances FitzGerald, Stanley Karnow, Brendan O'Leary, George Packer, Todd Shepard, Fred Smoler, and Stanley Weintraub.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 4aHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Essays.2bisacsh  aEuropean History.  aHistory.  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.  aWorld History.1 aAvineri, Shlomo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBhargava, Rajeev, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBromwich, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFitzgerald, Frances, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarnow, Stanley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMills, Nicolaus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMills, Nicolaus, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMoler, Freds, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca